# ORM Patterns and Tools

ORMs map application objects to database rows, letting you work with code-level abstractions instead of raw SQL. They handle connection management, query building, result mapping, and often include [[database/migrations]] tooling. Understanding the underlying [[database/sql]] remains essential for debugging ORM-generated queries and writing optimized operations.

## Patterns

### Active Record

The model class itself handles persistence. Instances know how to save, update, and delete themselves:

```javascript
// Sequelize (Active Record)
const user = await User.create({ name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' });
user.name = 'Alicia';
await user.save();
await user.destroy();
```

**Pros:** Simple, intuitive, less boilerplate. **Cons:** Tight coupling between domain logic and persistence, harder to test in isolation.

### Data Mapper

Separate repository or mapper classes handle persistence. Domain objects are plain objects:

```typescript
// TypeORM (Data Mapper)
const userRepo = dataSource.getRepository(User);
const user = userRepo.create({ name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' });
await userRepo.save(user);
await userRepo.remove(user);
```

**Pros:** Clean separation of concerns, easier to test, domain objects stay pure. **Cons:** More boilerplate, more abstractions to learn.

## Prisma

Schema-first ORM with auto-generated, type-safe client. Declarative schema in `schema.prisma` drives migrations and code generation.

```prisma
// prisma/schema.prisma
datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

model User {
  id        Int      @id @default(autoincrement())
  name      String
  email     String   @unique
  posts     Post[]
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
}

model Post {
  id       Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  title    String
  author   User   @relation(fields: [authorId], references: [id])
  authorId Int
}
```

```typescript
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';
const prisma = new PrismaClient();

// Create with relation
const user = await prisma.user.create({
  data: {
    name: 'Alice',
    email: 'alice@example.com',
    posts: { create: { title: 'First Post' } },
  },
  include: { posts: true },
});

// Query with filtering and pagination
const users = await prisma.user.findMany({
  where: { email: { contains: '@example.com' } },
  orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' },
  take: 20,
  skip: 0,
});
```

See [[database/migrations#tools-comparison]] for Prisma Migrate details.

## Drizzle

Lightweight TypeScript ORM with SQL-like query API. Schema defined in TypeScript, compiles to SQL.

```typescript
import { pgTable, serial, text, timestamp } from 'drizzle-orm/pg-core';
import { drizzle } from 'drizzle-orm/node-postgres';
import { eq } from 'drizzle-orm';
import { Pool } from 'pg';

const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name').notNull(),
  email: text('email').notNull().unique(),
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at').defaultNow(),
});

const pool = new Pool({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL });
const db = drizzle(pool);

// Insert
await db.insert(users).values({ name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' });

// Select with filter
const result = await db.select().from(users).where(eq(users.email, 'alice@example.com'));
```

## Python ORMs

### SQLAlchemy

```python
from sqlalchemy import create_engine, Column, Integer, String, DateTime
from sqlalchemy.orm import declarative_base, Session
from datetime import datetime

Base = declarative_base()

class User(Base):
    __tablename__ = 'users'
    id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True)
    name = Column(String, nullable=False)
    email = Column(String, nullable=False, unique=True)
    created_at = Column(DateTime, default=datetime.utcnow)

engine = create_engine("postgresql://user:pass@localhost/mydb")
Base.metadata.create_all(engine)

with Session(engine) as session:
    user = User(name='Alice', email='alice@example.com')
    session.add(user)
    session.commit()

    users = session.query(User).filter(User.email.contains('@example.com')).all()
```

## When to Use an ORM

| Scenario | Recommendation |
|----------|----------------|
| Standard CRUD applications | ORM — reduces boilerplate, prevents SQL injection |
| Complex reporting queries | Raw SQL or query builder — ORMs struggle with complex joins and CTEs |
| High-performance bulk operations | Raw SQL — ORMs add overhead per-row |
| Rapid prototyping | ORM — faster iteration on schema and queries |
| Multi-database support | ORM — abstracts dialect differences |
| Simple scripts or one-off queries | Raw SQL or query builder (Knex) |

When the ORM generates inefficient queries, use [[database/indexing#explain-analyze]] to diagnose and consider dropping to raw SQL for that specific query.
